  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Adjective Agreement",
      "titleArabic": "الصِّفَة",
      "content": [
        "In Arabic, adjectives (sifa) follow the noun they describe and must agree in four ways: gender, number, definiteness, and case.",
        "For feminine nouns, adjectives add taa marbuta (ة). For definite nouns, adjectives also take ال. The adjective mirrors the noun's grammatical state."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Adjectives come after the noun (opposite of English)",
        "Adjectives agree in gender: كِتَابٌ جَدِيدٌ (masc.) vs سَيَّارَةٌ جَدِيدَةٌ (fem.)",
        "Adjectives agree in definiteness: كِتَابٌ جَدِيدٌ vs الْكِتَابُ الْجَدِيدُ",
        "This pattern is called نَعْتٌ (description) in Arabic grammar"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "كِتَابٌ جَدِيدٌ", "english": "a new book" },
        { "arabic": "سَيَّارَةٌ جَمِيلَةٌ", "english": "a beautiful car" },
        { "arabic": "الْبَيْتُ الْكَبِيرُ", "english": "the big house" },
        { "arabic": "الْغُرْفَةُ الصَّغِيرَةُ", "english": "the small room" }
      ]
    }
  ],
